05609nam a22008415i 9780812205282DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112010pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122052827 a10.9783/97808122052822doi  a(DE-B1597)449386  a(OCoLC)979954215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHT167b.G55 2010eb 7aPOL0030002bisacsh04a307.1/21609732221 aGillette, Jr., Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCivitas by Design :bBuilding Better Communities, from the Garden City to the New Urbanism /cHoward Gillette, Jr. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b36 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Progressive Reform Through Environmental Intervention -- tChapter 2. The Garden City in America -- tChapter 3. The City: Film as Artifact -- tChapter 4. The Evolution of Neighborhood Planning -- tChapter 5. The Planned Shopping Center in Suburb and City -- tChapter 6. James Rouse and American City Planning -- tChapter 7. The New Urbanism: ‘‘Organizing Things That Matter -- tChapter 8. Civitas in the Design of Low-Income Housing -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the end of the nineteenth century, city planners have aspired not only to improve the physical living conditions of urban residents but also to strengthen civic ties through better design of built environments. From Ebenezer Howard and his vision for garden cities to today's New Urbanists, these visionaries have sought to deepen civitas, or the shared community of citizens.In Civitas by Design, historian Howard Gillette, Jr., takes a critical look at this planning tradition, examining a wide range of environmental interventions and their consequences over the course of the twentieth century. As American reform efforts moved from progressive idealism through the era of government urban renewal programs to the rise of faith in markets, planners attempted to cultivate community in places such as Forest Hills Gardens in Queens, New York; Celebration, Florida; and the post-Katrina Gulf Coast. Key figures—including critics Lewis Mumford and Oscar Newman, entrepreneur James Rouse, and housing reformer Catherine Bauer—introduced concepts such as neighborhood units, pedestrian shopping malls, and planned communities that were implemented on a national scale. Many of the buildings, landscapes, and infrastructures that planners envisioned still remain, but frequently these physical designs have proven insufficient to sustain the ideals they represented. Will contemporary urbanists' efforts to join social justice with environmentalism generate better results? Gillette places the work of reformers and designers in the context of their times, providing a careful analysis of the major ideas and trends in urban planning for current and future policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCommunity developmentzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aUrbanizationzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aAmerican History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aUrban Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUnive